@incollection{Hull2004,
abstract = {This chapter reviews research on the association of alcohol and self-regulation and reaches several conclusions. First, although individuals low in self-control are more likely to drink to excess, individuals often consume alcohol in a specific attempt to exert control over their affective and cognitive experiences. Second, although these effects are to some extent driven by the pharmacological effect of alcohol, expectancies regarding the effects of the drug also influence various aspects of alcohol consumption. Third, given that alcohol consumption is influenced by expectancies, it is important to understand the variables that shape these expectancies. Fourth, although alcohol would appear to have generally deleterious effects on self-regulation, these effects are neither simple nor straightforward. Fifth, despite the fact that various candidates have been offered as attentional, cognitive, and affective mediators of the impact of alcohol on self-regulation, definitive support for any one psychological mechanism is lacking. Ultimately, although progress has been made in understanding how alcohol affects self-regulation, additional research is necessary to illuminate precisely why it has these effects as well as the conditions necessary to overcome these effects. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2019 APA, all rights reserved)},
